Project 1¶

Investigate Trends of Patients Who Do or Do Not Show Up for Medical Appointments¶

DATASET: noshowappointments-kagglev2-may-2016.csv¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

Not everyone keeps their medical appointments, and this depends on several factors. This analysis hopes to explore various factors that might determine whether or not a patient keeps their medical appointments, according the the variable present in the dataset above.

Questions¶

The following questions will be explored:

  1. Which gender is more likely to keep appointments?
  2. Are people from a particular neighborhood more likely to keep appointments?
  3. How does age affect the likelihood of a patient keeping their appointments?
  4. How does the time lag between scheduling and actual appointment day affect appointment-keeping?
  5. Does disability prevent a patient from keeping appointments, and does this depend on number of disabilities?
  6. Does the scholarship(a form of health insurance) enable people keep their appointments more?
  7. Does Hypertension make a patient keener to keep appointments?
  8. How do Diabetics fare with appointments?
  9. Does Alcoholism interfere with a patient's appointment-keeping?
  10. Are SMS reminders effective?

Before getting started, all needed libraries will be imported.

  1. Pandas for dataframe operations
  2. Numpy as needed for supporting Pandas
  3. Datetime to correctly format columns holding dates
  4. Matplotlib for plotting
  5. Seaborn for styling plots
  6. Gridspec to efficiently organize plots into grids.

Summary of Dataset¶

The dataset contains details of patients who did or did not show up for their appointments.

  • PatientId: ID of the patient
  • AppointmentID: Unique ID for appointments.
  • Gender: M or F
  • ScheduledDay: The day the appointment was scheduled.
  • AppointmentDay: The day of the appointment.
  • Age: Of Patient
  • Neighborhood: Where patient resides.
  • Scholarship: Whether or not the patient is enrolled in the welfare program.
  • Hypertension: Is patient hypertensive or not?
  • Diabetes: Diabetic or not?
  • Alcoholism: alcoholic or not?
  • Handicap: Handicapped or not?
  • SMS_received: did patient receive SMS reminder for appointment?
  • No-show: Did the patient show up? Yes means it's a no-show(i.e., patient didn't show up).

There appears to be no missing values anywhere in the dataset, therefore, there is no need to fill in any mising values.

Renaming Columns¶

For ease of manipulating later, columns will be renames to convert to all lowercase and replace spaces with underscores.

Columns like PatientId and SchduledDay can be better read as patient_id and scheduled_day respectively.

Some colum names are misspelt, Hipertension and Handcap.

In [6]:
# Performing the first operation

df.rename(columns={'patientid':'patient_id',

                    'hipertension':'hypertension',
                    'handcap':'handicap',
                    'no-show':'no_show',
                    'scheduledday': 'scheduled_day',
                    'appointmentday': 'appointment_day'
                    }, inplace=True)

Dealing with Data Types¶

Since patient_id's are unique, they best be int rather than float

scheduled_day and appointment_day columns should be converted to regular datetime objects. The dates will be extracted and the time fragments discarded, as they will not be relevant. Afterall, an observation of the appointment_day column shows all the time fragments as 00:00:00

In [8]:
# converting patient_id's to int
df.patient_id = df.patient_id.astype(int)
In [9]:
# dealing with datetime
df.scheduled_day = df.scheduled_day.apply(lambda x: dt.strptime(x.split('T')[0], '%Y-%m-%d'))
df.appointment_day = df.appointment_day.apply(lambda x: dt.strptime(x.split('T')[0], '%Y-%m-%d'))

    neigh_df = df[df.neighbourhood==neigh]  # dataframe of appointments pertaining to a particular neighborhood

    neigh_total = len(neigh_df)
    neigh_kept = len(df_kept)
    neigh_missed = neigh_total - neigh_kept
    neigh_percent = round(((neigh_kept/neigh_total) * 100) ,2)

    temp.append((neigh, neigh_total, neigh_kept, neigh_missed, neigh_percent))

neigh_props_df = pd.DataFrame(temp, columns=('neighborhood', 'total_appts', 'kept_appts', 'missed_appts', '%_kept'))

Generic Functions¶

Two generic functions will be defined to handle much of the rest of the operations. The columns typically have a feature with 0 or 1 to mark its absence or presence. For each of these, the proportions of appointments kept where the feature is present and where it is absent will be compared with bar plots.

In [61]:
# Function to calculate and return values needed

def check_feature(feature_name):

    """ Since some features are represented by 0 for present and 1 for absent,
    the proportions of patients that show up can be derived with one function as thus:"""

    feature = len(df[df[feature_name]==1])
    feature_show = len(df[(df[feature_name]==1) & (df['no_show']=='No')])
    feature_noshow = feature - feature_show
    feature_show_prop = round((feature_show / feature)*100, 2)

    no_feature = len(df[df[feature_name]==0])
    no_feature_show = len(df[(df[feature_name]==0) & (df['no_show']=='No')])
    no_feature_noshow = no_feature - no_feature_show
    no_feature_show_prop = round((no_feature_show / no_feature)*100, 2)

    return feature, feature_show, feature_noshow, feature_show_prop, \
    no_feature, no_feature_show, no_feature_noshow, no_feature_show_prop
In [73]:
def plot_feature(feature_name,\
                    feature, feature_show, feature_show_prop,\
                    no_feature, no_feature_show, no_feature_show_prop):

    """ A single function can also be used to plot those features"""

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    gs = GridSpec(nrows=2, ncols=2)
    
    ax = fig.add_subplot(gs[:,0])
    X = np.arange(0,2)
    ax.bar(X-0.2, [feature, feature_show], 0.4, label=f'{feature_name.title()}')
    ax.bar(X+0.2, [no_feature, no_feature_show], 0.4, label=f'Not {feature_name.title()}')
    ax.set_xticks(X, ['Show Up', 'No Show'])
    ax.set_xlabel('Appointment Kept Status')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of Patients')
    ax.set_title(f'Total Appointments by {feature_name.title()}')
    ax.legend()

    ax = fig.add_subplot(gs[:,1])
    ax.bar(x=[f'{feature_name.title()}', f'Not {feature_name.title()}'],
            height=[feature_show_prop, no_feature_show_prop])
    ax.set_xlabel(f'{feature_name.title()} Status')
    ax.set_ylabel('Proportion(%)')
    ax.set_title(f'Proportion of Patients that Show Up by {feature_name.title()}')

# get unique disability counts and their corresponding proportions
disability_counts = df.handicap.unique()
the_props = []
for count in disability_counts:
    dis_count = len(df[df.handicap==count])
    dis_show_count = len(df[(df.handicap==count) & (df.no_show=='No')])
    the_props.append(round((dis_show_count/dis_count)*100, 2))
In [71]:
# plot bar to compare
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))

ax = fig.add_subplot()
ax.bar(disability_counts, the_props)
ax.set_xlabel('Number of Disabilities')
ax.set_ylabel('Proportion that Show up for Appointments(%)')
ax.set_title('Appointment Kept by Disability')
Out[71]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Appointment Kept by Disability')

There is certainly a clear trend here. People with just 1 disability are more likely to keep their appointments than those with no 0 disability. However, beyond that, the rate drops with increasing number of disabilities.

Conclusions¶

This is a summary of conclusions drawn from exploring the dataset.

  1. Females make more appointments than males (65% to 35% of the total appointments), however, they are not more likely to keep them. The proportion of males and females who keep their appointments are about equal, with 79.7% and 80% of females and males respectively keeping their appointments.
  2. Aside from the neighborhood ILHAS OCEANICA DE TRINDADE, at least 70% of appointments from a neighborhood are kept, with the least being 71.08% for SANTOS DUMONT. Excluding PARQUE INDUSTRIAL with just one appointment and 100% rate, ILHA DA BOI has the highest rate with 91.43%
  3. There is definitely a trend in appointments kept by age. Generally, rate is high at birth (at about 82%), but then it drops with increasing age until the late teens(about 70%), after which the rate increases again till around 70 years of age (about 85%), after which it declines again as age sets in.
  4. Most appointments are done within two weeks, and the other time_lags do not appear frequently enough to give a good depiction. However, one can infer that for about 6 weeks, appointments drop as well as rate of show-up's.
  5. There is a trend in disabilities too. On the initial comparison of rates, it seems people with disabilities keep appointments more. However, further investigation reaveals that this is only so for patients with just one disability. Patients with two disabilites or more are increasingly less likely to keep their appointments, with the rate decreasing with increasing number of disabilities.
  6. From this dataset, it appears that people on the Scholarship are not more likely to keep their appointments. 90.2 were not on Scholarship, and only 9.2 were covered. Probably, more needs to be done to cover more patients under the scholarship. However, in relating to keeping appointments, people covered by the scholarship are slightly less likely to keep appointments(76.3%) compared to those without it(80.2). This gap is not however significant enough to conclude definitively.
  7. Patients with long-terms illnesses are slightly more likely to keep their appointments, as is apparent by the hypertension and diabetes features of this dataset.
  8. Though alcoholics are only a small fraction of the total, surprisingly, the alcoholics in this dataset do not lag in keeping their appointments. A computation actually shows 79.85% of the alcoholics in this dataset show up, while 79.80% of the non-alcoholics keep appointments.
  9. Again, only a very little proportion of the patients get SMS reminders (just above 30%). However, the SMS reminders do not appear to be effective, since more than 80% of those who do not get SMS show up, whereas only slightly above 70% of those who got the SMS reminders eventually showed up.
DISCLAIMER¶

This exploration is based only on a single dataset from a single region. While it does give some useful insights, it does not claim to be an absolute representation of trends all over the world or even in the locality from which the dataset has been collected.
